docs.abstract: On television and in print, Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh on Monday began a remarkable campaign to defend his nomination to the Supreme Court, even as new accusations emerged.
docs.snippet: On television and in print, Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh on Monday began a remarkable campaign to defend his nomination to the Supreme Court, even as new accusations emerged.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh, facing new allegations of sexual impropriety and growing doubts over his confirmation to the Supreme Court, mounted an aggressive defense of himself on Monday, vowing to fight the “smears” and declaring that he will not withdraw his nomination.

headline.main: Brett Kavanaugh Vows to Fight ‘Smears’ and Will Not Withdraw
headline.print_headline: Trump’s Nominee Vows to Stand Up Against ‘Smears’

docs.abstract: Dianne Feinstein, the ranking Democrat on the Senate Judiciary Committee, announced she has referred a matter involving Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh to federal investigators.
docs.snippet: Dianne Feinstein, the ranking Democrat on the Senate Judiciary Committee, announced she has referred a matter involving Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh to federal investigators.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The senior Democrat on the Senate Judiciary Committee referred information involving Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh, President Trump’s nominee to the Supreme Court, to federal investigators on Thursday, but the senator declined to make public what the matter involved.

headline.main: Dianne Feinstein Refers a Kavanaugh Matter to Federal Investigators

docs.abstract: Facing an uphill battle for re-election, Senator Heidi Heitkamp of North Dakota raised a staggering $12.5 million in 17 days.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — After Senator Heidi Heitkamp of North Dakota announced that she would not vote to confirm Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh to the Supreme Court, sympathetic voters went to work to show their support for the embattled red-state Democrat, writing letters of thanks and posting their appreciation on social media.

headline.main: A ‘No’ on Kavanaugh Yields a Windfall for Heitkamp’s Campaign Coffers

docs.abstract: The head of the House Republican campaign arm all but jettisoned Representative Steve King of Iowa, declaring “we must stand up against white supremacy.”
docs.snippet: The head of the House Republican campaign arm all but jettisoned Representative Steve King of Iowa, declaring “we must stand up against white supremacy.”
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — As Pittsburgh began burying the victims of Saturday’s synagogue massacre, the head of the House Republican campaign arm all but jettisoned Representative Steve King of Iowa from the House Republican Conference, declaring, “We must stand up against white supremacy and hate in all forms.”

headline.main: Standing ‘Against White Supremacy,’ G.O.P. Campaign Chief Rebukes Steve King

docs.abstract: The Senate is weighing whether to rechristen the Russell Senate Building, named after a senator who promoted racial segregation, to honor John McCain.
docs.snippet: The Senate is weighing whether to rechristen the Russell Senate Building, named after a senator who promoted racial segregation, to honor John McCain.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The names of three men who once dominated the Senate’s halls of power are lettered in gold onto each limestone front of the stately Senate office buildings just across from the Capitol — honorifics reserved for an elite few.

headline.main: Replace Richard Russell’s Name With McCain’s? Senate Debates a Segregationist’s Legacy
headline.print_headline: A Segregationist’s Legacy Back in the Conversation

docs.abstract: The next speaker will be elected on Jan. 3. To muster enough support, Nancy Pelosi is striking deals with members of her caucus. Here are some of those bargains.
docs.snippet: The next speaker will be elected on Jan. 3. To muster enough support, Nancy Pelosi is striking deals with members of her caucus. Here are some of those bargains.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Representative Nancy Pelosi overwhelmingly won the Democratic nomination last month to be speaker, but the defection of 32 Democratic dissidents left her short of the votes she would need to win the gavel in January, when she can lose only 17.

headline.main: What Pelosi Has Promised to Win Speaker Votes
